\begin_layout Section
What evidence of such a link exists?
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:eq-swb-evidence"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Researchers in urban planning, epidemiology and psychology have pursued
 observational and experimental evidence on links between physical or mental
 wellbeing and EQ.
 Economists have sought observational evidence of links between happiness
 and EQ, generally using these to derive monetary valuations of EQ characteristi
cs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Studies outside economics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Studies-outside-economics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observational studies have compared individuals' health and wellbeing reports
 or medical records with the proximity of their homes to natural environments,
 or with alternative indicators of local environmental quality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "kaplan:2001,takano:2002,vries:2003,grahn:2003,maas:2006,nielsen:2007,bjork:2008a,maas:2009"

\end_inset

.
 On occasion they have also related averaged wellbeing measures to aggregate
 environmental characteristics between geographical regions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "mitchell:2007"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimental and quasi-experimental studies have investigated physiological
 and psychological effects of exposure to images of different environment
 types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "berto:2005,white:2010,ryan:2010"

\end_inset

 or to short-term interventions bringing subjects into contact with nature
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "hartig:2003,pretty:2007,berman:2008,barton:2010,ryan:2010,martens:2011"

\end_inset

.
 They have also related health and wellbeing indicators to views of nature
 in settings where individuals' accommodation is assigned exogenously: public
 housing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kuo:2001a"

\end_inset

, prisons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "moore:1981"

\end_inset

, and hospitals (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "ulrich:1984"

\end_inset

's much-cited 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "ulrich:1984"

\end_inset

 paper in 
\emph on
Science
\emph default
, 'View through a window may influence recovery from surgery').
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Though all of these studies report beneficial impacts of natural environments
 on health or wellbeing, they have some common weaknesses.
 Observational studies measure domestic proximity to natural environments
 but rarely look at actual experiences of such environments (which may or
 may not occur around the home, and may occur elsewhere); cannot provide
 data on the moment-by-moment hedonic or affective element of wellbeing;
 and are reliant on retrospective assessments that are subject to substantial
 recall bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "robinson:2002"

\end_inset

.
 Experimental studies are stronger in these respects but --- with the possible
 exception of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "kuo:2001a"

\end_inset

's --- are generally low in ecological validity: by their nature they tell
 us a limited amount about peoples' real experiences of natural environments
 in their everyday lives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Studies in conventional economics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:eq-conventional-economic-studies"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Refer back to lit review
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In economics, relationships between location and quality of life have long
 been a subject of interest in the hedonic pricing literature, in which
 environmental and urban amenities have been used to account for regional
 wage and rent differentials and construct 'objective' quality of life indices
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roback:1982"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "roback-ref-response"

\end_inset

.
 Hedonic valuation has been used to investigate the impacts of various dimension
s of EQ, including road noise, air quality, water quality, forests, wetlands,
 view of nature, urban trees and open spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "smith:2010"

\end_inset

 finds that each hectare of parkland within 1km increases London house prices
 by 0.08%, while a large park within 600 metres adds 2 -- 3% to a house's
 value, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gibbons:2011a"

\end_inset

 find that local green space, water, woodland and farmland attract a considerabl
e house price premium in England, while increasing distance to natural amenities
 such as rivers and National Parks is associated with a fall in house prices.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gibbons:2011a"

\end_inset

 also provide a more complete survey of studies of this type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hedonic pricing studies have most commonly used only distances as indicators
 of EQ characteristics, although the two studies cited exploit improved
 GIS capabilities to also consider the local quantities of certain amenities.
\end_layout

