\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

 find that close proximity to coastline (within 2km or in the same local
 authority area respectively) has a positive association with SWB, but 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 find no significant effect of coastline within 5km.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Biodiversity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rehdanz:2007a"

\end_inset

 runs spatial regression models with country-level data on simple counts
 of bird and mammal species, and the proportions of species that are threatened,
 and suggests that greater numbers of species, and lower proportions of
 bird species threatened, are associated with higher SWB.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Natural capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vemuri:2006"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "engelbrecht:2009"

\end_inset

 report positive relationships between indicators of wellbeing and generalised
 'natural capital' at country level.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "vemuri:2006"

\end_inset

 measure natural capital as the 'ecosystem services product' based on land
 cover types 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sutton:2002"

\end_inset

, which can arguably be considered EQ-related.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "engelbrecht:2009"

\end_inset

's natural capital figures do not appear to be appropriate EQ measures,
 however, since reserves of resources such as metal ores, oil and coal feature
 heavily.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Limitations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:econ-eq-swb-Limitations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Country-level studies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several studies compare mean SWB and mean EQ values at the whole-country
 level (all Welsch's air pollution papers cited above; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "israel:2003,rehdanz:2005,rehdanz:2007a,vemuri:2006,engelbrecht:2009,menz:2010"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "israel:2003"

\end_inset

 use SWB data at individual level but pollution data at whole-country level
 (and include only per capita GDP to control for any other differences between
 countries that might be correlated with pollution emissions).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Although this has the advantage that unobserved heterogeneity across individual
s is evened out, it means that SWB and EQ levels are assessed only on an
 extremely aggregated scale --- with no indication of variability or of
 actual EQ exposures --- and that other sources of heterogeneity across
 countries, including linguistic and cultural heterogeneity, then need to
 be controlled for
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, Welsch (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2002"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2007"

\end_inset

) purports to control for heterogeneity between 54 countries using only
 per capita income, 'rationality' (the number of scientists and engineers
 per thousand people) and --- in the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2002"

\end_inset

 but not the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2007"

\end_inset

 paper --- 'freedom' (as assessed on a 1--7 scale by an American NGO).
 Welsch's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2003"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "welsch:2006"

\end_inset

 papers use panel data with country and period dummy variables to better
 address unobserved international heterogeneity.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 It also requires a cardinal interpretation of SWB responses (though in
 practice, as discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:SWB-variable-treatment"

\end_inset

, this tends not to be problematic).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Individual-level studies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The remaining papers use individual-level SWB data, controlling for various
 demographic, socio-economic and attitudinal variables in addition to indicators
 of EQ near respondents' homes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A major limitation of most of these studies remains the level of spatial
 aggregation of EQ measures, which are rarely at better (and frequently
 at worse) than electoral ward level.
 The use of such spatially aggregated statistics leads to reduced accuracy,
 to an extent which may be problematic in the case of characteristics varying
 over short distances, such as noise or air pollution
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 use relatively disaggregated measures, mainly calculated per electoral
 district (area: 18 to 6,189 hectares).
 However, their indicators of air pollution, which may vary over very short
 distances, are calculated by proximity to one or more of only 12 monitoring
 stations for the whole of Ireland.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mackerron:2008"

\end_inset

 use exceptionally high resolution air pollution data (20m cells), but this
 study is weakened by the probable existence of omitted spatial covariates
 and by its reliance for SWB measures on a small convenience sample.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 It also raises the Modifiable Areal Unit Problem (MAUP): it could be that
 substantially different results would have been obtained if measurements
 had been aggregated across different spatial units 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "openshaw:1984"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even where EQ near the home is estimated accurately, that quantity may itself
 not correspond closely to an individual's actual exposure to or experience
 of EQ.
 For example, exposure in or near the home to certain kinds of air pollution
 may account for only a small fraction of the total variation in exposure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "huang:2000"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In common with studies in other disciplines, those in economics have commonly
 focused on only a single EQ parameter (e.g.
 noise), despite probable correlations of that parameter with other EQ and
 broader spatial characteristics (e.g.
 air pollution, land cover type, transport amenities)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The studies using Irish data by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "brereton:2007"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 are exceptions here.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This omission of a broader range of spatial variables in general seems
 liable to lead to endogeneity.
 Furthermore, since EQ differentials may be compensated by wages and house
 prices, differing approaches regarding the inclusion of income and house
 price data mean that different studies turn out to be measuring different
 things (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:happiness-valuation"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
None of the studies addresses the potential influence on SWB of green space,
 such as grassland or forest, despite the evidence from other disciplines
 that green space has a positive wellbeing effect.
 Few have considered 'blue space' --- coastal or freshwater environments
 --- while those that have (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "brereton:2007"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

) include only distance to the coast.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Apart from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "engelbrecht:2009"

\end_inset

's, none of the studies investigate the sensitivity of their results to
 the use of alternative SWB items, and none make use of potentially more
 robust multiple-item SWB scales.
 Perhaps surprisingly given the spatial nature of the data, only one study
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rehdanz:2007a"

\end_inset

 turns to spatial econometric models, as have recently been used in hedonic
 pricing studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "kim:2008,anselin:2008"

\end_inset

.
 Such models could help address problems of omitted spatial covariates (in
 the case of spatial error models) and inefficiencies in non-spatial estimators
 (for spatial lag models)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The usefulness of these spatial models has been questioned by some researchers,
 however 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gibbons:2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Finally, only one study 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "luechinger:2009"

\end_inset

 offers a convincing strategy for the identification of causal effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
No experience-level studies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:domains-and-timescales"

\end_inset

, longitudinal study designs in which participants provide ongoing reports
 of their everyday experience --- Ecological Momentary Assessment (EMA)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "shiffman:2008"

\end_inset

, the Experience Sampling Method (ESM) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hektner:2007"

\end_inset

, and the Day Reconstruction Method (DRM) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kahneman:2004a"

\end_inset

 --- provide some of the best, most ecologically valid evidence regarding
 influences on wellbeing in general.
 None of the studies cited in this section (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:eq-swb-evidence"

\end_inset

) --- nor any studies of EQ in any discipline, as far as we are aware ---
 draw on data on the moment-by-moment hedonic or affective element of wellbeing
 collected in this way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Summary and conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In sum, there are good reasons to hypothesise that EQ levels will be positively
 related to SWB, and the existing evidence from a variety of experimental
 and observational sources --- in happiness economics, other economic studies,
 and beyond --- appears to point in this direction.
 We have identified a number of limitations of the existing evidence, focusing
 particularly on work in economics on happiness and EQ.
 In this thesis we attempt to rectify several, but not all, of these.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:research-aims"

\end_inset

, we conduct two strands of new empirical research.
 One makes significant but evolutionary improvements to the earlier work
 modelling retrospective happiness evaluations as a function of EQ in the
 local area, using cross-sectional, individual-level data.
 These improvements were detailed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:intro-surveys"

\end_inset

.
 The other takes a somewhat more pioneering direction, investigating momentary
 happiness reports as a function of EQ in their immediate surroundings,
 using experience sampling techniques augmented with objective spatial measures,
 as explained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:intro-esm"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following three chapters set out the methods employed in this connection.
 They cover our survey and ESM data collection methods, and describe the
 spatial and econometric analyses subsequently applied.
\end_layout

